.. using a standard antisymmetrization trick. Also

+ Add lemmas `wellFoundedLT/GT_antisymmetrization_iff`.

+ Establish the `OrderIso` between the antisymmetrization of a product preorder and the product of antisymmetrizations.

+ Golf the original `Prod.wellFoundedLT` and rename it to `Prod.wellFoundedLT'`.

+ Golf `StrictMono.wellFoundedLT` etc. and move to where `StrictMono` is defined.

Does it make sense to provide `simp` lemmas here? e.g. `Antisymmetrization.prodEquiv âŸ¦xâŸ§ = (âŸ¦x.1âŸ§, âŸ¦x.2âŸ§)`, etc.

This feels like a somewhat random file to put these instances in. What's the reasoning?

I'm using both StrictMono.wellFoundedLT into Antisymmetrization in the proofs, which don't import each other. When I tried to imported StrictMono.wellFoundedLT into Antisymmetrization I got +16.91% increase in transitive imports and was [warned by the bot](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/17435#issuecomment-2394988628). `#find_home` found this order theory file that imports both, but now I've figured out the correct solution is to golf the proof of StrictMono.wellFoundedLT and move it to where StrictMono is defined ...
